@node Film "Film at Eleven"

    _____
   / _   )                   Film at Eleven
  / / ) /                    by @{" Jim Meyer " link jim}
 / (_/ / 
(_____/ ne of the advantages of using a Mac LC II connected via AppleTalk
to a laser imager for heavy-duty production is that you have a lot of
spare time on your hands.  There are those endless minutes spent waiting
for the screen to update or tasks to switch, and hours spent waiting for
output.  Fortunately, I have an SII Coyote editing terminal on my desk
which has access to the AP Newswire. This provides me with more
entertainment than one person should have. One of the items I came across
recently was a story on 2 new Macintoshes: the Centris 660AV and the
Quadra 840AV.  The fun starts in the first paragraph, where these systems
are described as "mid-priced."  Of course, this is probably from the pen
of a writer who can use the terms "PC" and "easy to use" in the same
sentence.  I now present that story, embellished with the information
that seemed to be missing:

"Apple Computer Inc. plans to introduce a new line of mid-priced
Macintosh computers that talk, recognize voice commands, and read text
back to the user.  Although talking and reading text back to the user
might appear to be the same thing, Apple feels that this one feature can
be made to appear as two by wording it this way.

Apple said that these models would sell for between $2,139 and $6,249,
depending upon how gullible the consumer seemed to be.

Apple's PlainTalk speech recognition software, which may well have been
ripped off from similar Shareware efforts for the Amiga, allows the
machine to misunderstand spoken commands such as "Open File" or "Move
Text" or "Spit out the darn disk NOW!"  Furthermore, it will be able to
read text back in a synthesized voice.

'No other personal computer on the market today can provide all of these
capabilities,' said Ian Diery, completely oblivious to the 4 million
Amigas which have had these capabilities since 1985.

Apple plans to introduce a new color display terminal with built-in
stereo speakers at the phenomenally low price of $800.  When confronted
with the fact that this new monitor, at 640 X 400 resolution, was nothing
more than a VGA monitor with built-in Labtec speakers (Retail: $29.95),
Apple had no comment.  Nor did they have anything to say when it was
pointed out that the consumer could spend $300 or less for a comparable
monitor, and then still have $500 to spend on a stereo system that was
far superior than that provided by the Apple monitor."

I had just barely begun to stop laughing when I came across the results
of the lawsuit brought by Lotus against Borland.  Lotus won their
copyright infringement suit.  Among other things, the judge ruled that
Quattro, marketed by Borland, had copied such things as menu commands,
menu structure, and - perhaps worst of all - the macro key.  I wonder if
it's too late to patent the Save command?

And then I read a story about a 17-year-old computer enthusiast who got
10 years probation for paying an undercover investigator to kill the
boyfriend of a girl he had a crush on.  The payment?  $5.30 and 7 Atari
cartridges.  Perhaps it's just the sick-o in me, but I could have sworn
the going rate was 9 Atari cartridges...

@EndNode

@node sigg "SIGGRAPH 93"

 ______
(__  __)                        SIGGRAPH 93
  / /                       by @{" Dennis Schaefer " link Dennis }
 / /  
(_/ his year the SIGGRAPH convention landed in my backyard - Anaheim,
California. SIGGRAPH is, in case you don't know, the world's oldest,
largest and most prestigious of gatherings of people and things relating to
computer graphics. The moniker refers to "Special Interest Group GRAPHICS."
Yes folks, all the big boys were there.

Although the Anaheim Convention Center is across the street from
Disneyland, I did not expect to stand in the Disneyland-type line that
snaked across the lobby. In the forty-five minutes of waiting I did have
plenty of time to peruse the program. In the single afternoon that I spent
there, I knew I would not have time to attend any of the many classes and
seminars with such intriguing titles as "Recent Techniques in Human
Modeling, Animation and Rendering", "How to Lie and Confuse with
Visualization" and "Nan-o-Sex and Virtual Seduction." (!) Not to mention
installation artworks using machine intelligence and virtual reality
(hereinafter referred to as "VR") as "Nuero Baby" and "B*rbie's Virtual
Playhouse." The descriptions of these things are too long to go into here,
but were intriguing to say the least. But I had three large halls of
exhibits to get through, and that was enough! While waiting in line I was
able to pick out a few company names that were familiar to this
increasingly-humble Amiga user, and I resolved to visit them all. All six
of them that is.

The largest exhibits were those belonging to the companies that make
software that runs on high-end workstations such as Silicon Graphics, Sun,
etc. The big three in this arena were Alias, Wavefront and SoftImage.
SoftImage hasn't done much that is very impressive lately, unless you liked
all the dinosaurs in "Jurassic Park"! The Wavefront exhibit boasted a
realtime interactive show in which a 3-d animated disembodied head talked,
moved and made lewd remarks to unfortunate female bystanders, all in
realtime and in response to changing events. The head would make comments
about the young women's hair, clothing and appearance, making it clear that
this was happening in realtime.  I walked into the middle of the exhibit
and found the libidinous author of these remarks decked out in sensors. He
had a VR-type headset on to detect his head movement with the addition of
motion sensors attached to his lips and chin so that the program could
sense his mouth movements. It did not look comfortable...

Evans and Sutherland makes both hardware and software for the killer
high-end military flight simulators. They had two virtual hang-gliders set
up, complete with harness and control bar. In these you could fly through a
"Blade-Runner" type city, amazingly detailed, complete with futuristic
vehicles zipping by, all rendering in real-time! I was able to participate
in another VR exhibit involving a whole town and surrounding countryside
that the user could "drive" through. Picture VistaPro pictures with the
addition of detailed buildings rolling by at 30 frames per second in
stereo! The price of gasoline at the local Mobil station was quite
reasonable at $1.32 for unleaded super....

I finally set off in search of my Amiga brethren. Unfortunately, two of
the Amiga vendors I hoped to see did not have the booths that were listed
in the program: Virtual Reality Laboratories Inc (makers of VistaPro) and
(amazingly!) NewTek. However I did find booths set up by ASDG (makers of
Art Department Professional), Centaur (Opalvision), Realsoft (Real 3d) and
Desktop Video World (publishers of AmigaWorld).

Of the above exhibitors only Centaur was showing products devoted to the
Amiga exclusively. All the others are branching out into other platforms.
At a booth run by a Toaster User's Group I ran into a couple of folks from
NewTek. They told me that they had not set up a booth so that they could
afford to throw a big party the night before to introduce their "Video
Toaster Screamer." Gosh, doesn't NewTek have a gift for product names?

The "Screamer" is the really big news for Amiga Users coming out of
this show. This is an external rendering engine for the Toaster that uses
four parallel MIPS R4400 - 64-bit superpipelined RISC processors. That
description (from the NewTek flyer) is beyond the technical specs of this
writer, but suffice to say that the thing is moving FAST! NewTek claims
that it delivers "twice the computing power of a Cray I supercomputer." It
will retail at $9,995.

As an average Amiga user, you might wonder why this is news for you...
After all, YOU can't afford ten grand for this thing! Well, the thing is
that this price is dirt cheap for the kind of 3-d rendering power it
provides. With shows like Spielberg's "Seaquest DSV" using Lightwave, it
means that more and more television shows will turn to Lightwave and the
Toaster to produce their special effects sequences. And they will need
experienced Lightwave users... It means job opportunities in big show-biz
markets for people who can run this stuff. Not to mention a little respect
in the computer community. And THAT we can all use.

Several companies were conspicuous by their absence. Impulse, (makers
of Imagine, probably the most popular Amiga 3-d program), and DMI, (makers
of several products that purport to compete directly with Silicon Graphics
workstations) were both no-shows. And the biggest disappointment was the
lack of presence by Commodore. Both IBM and Apple had large displays.
Multimedia was a major sub-theme at SIGGRAPH this year, but was the clear-
and-present leader in multimedia clear present? No. If Commodore wants to
be taken seriously by the graphics community it must show its face at
forums like SIGGRAPH.

SIGGRAPH was an amazing experience for this writer, and next year I
plan to take about five times as much time exploring the nooks and
crannies! If you have an interest in computer graphics and/or the future of
virtual entertainment and simulation, check it out in Florida next year.
SIGGRAPH returns to Southern California the year after.

