@node tv "Same Time, Same Channel"

 _  __  _                 Same Time, Same Channel
( \/  \/ )                 by @{" Bill Camarota " link billc }
 \      / 
  \_/\_/ hen asked to write an article for Viewport, I wondered what
would be interesting to Amiga users. After some careful consideration, I
have decided to discuss the role of the Amiga in a small market TV
station.

I work as the Art Director for NBC affiliate WMGM TV in Atlantic City,
New Jersey. My background consists of extensive work in graphic design
and photography. I have exhibited my work at the Eastman Kodak Gallery in
NYC as well as having two album covers to my credit. I was approached by
the General Manager of the station four years ago and asked if I wanted a
challenge. I was presently involved with computer artwork and jumped at
the chance to have my work aired on TV.

Since I was working with the Amiga in my own personal endeavors, I
decided to advise the station to purchase two Amiga workstations. I
quickly pumped the two machines up with 16 megs of memory and hard drives.

My first task was to implement graphics for our newscasts. At the time,
the news only had the ability to display text over video or a colored
background. Logo generation was impossible. This was accomplished with a
Chyron VP1 character generator. So, I decided to start to revamp the
process using Shereff Systems Pro Video character generator software.
This allowed me to use 16 color DPaint screens as backgrounds. Working
closely with the News Director, we decided on a "graphic look" for the
station's newscasts. Part of that look included full screen scoreboards
with official MLB, NHL, NFL and NBA logos, weathermaps, locators and
interview tags. Some of you may be thinking, "weathermaps &
scoreboards?". You must realize the station had NO graphic abilities
before I introduced the Amiga.

Now onto the reasons why I picked ProVideo for our titles and screens.
The first reason is the fact that the program is able to store and use up
to 26 banks of 100 pages each. I currently retain a library of 200 pages
that the operator uses to sequence for a newscast. No other program to
date has this enormous capacity. This, coupled with the ability to
preload all my backgrounds and call up pages instantaneously, makes
ProVideo a winner. The program is very quick to respond and has NEVER
crashed during a newscast. Plugging in and editing almost a hundred pages
for the news is a breeze. The final reason is that it is extremely easy
to learn.

Four years later, 50% of the newscast contains Amiga generated graphics.
We now incorporate "over the shoulder" corner inserts and animation
sequences for special series stories.

Well, this concludes my first article. Next month, I will be talking
about scanning and rendering logos, the backbone of my daily tasks. Also
discussed will be reproduction legalities. If anyone has any questions or
suggestions, I can be reached on GEnie. My mailbox address is W.CAMAROTA.
See you next month, SAME TIME, SAME CHANNEL.

