@node type "TypeSmith"
 ______
(__  __)  TypeSmith: The Professional Amiga Outline Font Editor
  / /                     by @{" Peter Jacobsen " link peterj }
 / /  
(_/ ypeSmith is a very capable outline font editor from Soft-Logik. With
it, one can create and edit PostScript, Compugraphic and Soft-Logik outline
fonts. You can also convert fonts amongst PostScript Type 1, Compugraphic
Intellifont and Soft-Logik DMF Outline formats. You can export to Post-
Script Type 3 format, but you cannot edit or load it.

With its powerful drawing tools you can create new fonts. You can also
import characters and symbols from structured drawing programs. This allows
you to create custom fonts or logos. Using Workbench 2.x or above, you can
load bitmapped pictures and Amiga bitmap fonts as templates so that you can
trace over them. Since TypeSmith does not directly support editing of Amiga
bitmap fonts, this feature gives you a way to create outline fonts from
your bitmap font collection.

I found TypeSmith very easy to use. I particularly liked TypeSmith's
ability to automatically create character widths, and to import kerning
pairs. This makes the editing job so much easier.  With other font editors
I've used, you had to do these things manually.

Not being an artistic person, I was at first reluctant to use the drawing
tools in TypeSmith. After a few aborted attempts, I was able to create my
first outline 'font'. With some practice, I found the tools quite easy to
use and better suited to creating fonts than turning pixels on/off in a
grid like bitmap font editors do.  Another nice feature I found useful, is
the ability to dump a font you're working on to the printer so you can
really see what it will look like. The print quality was excellent on my 24
pin dot matrix.

While I find that TypeSmith does an excellent job creating and editing
outline fonts, I was disappointed that it could not directly be able to
create or edit native Amiga bitmapped fonts. However, I am encouraged by
the fact that that may be added in a future update. Billing itself as 'the
Professional Amiga Font Editor' and not directly supporting bitmapped fonts
seemed odd to me. Even so, I have no problem recommending TypeSmith to
someone who is interested in creating/editing outline fonts.

TypeSmith uses a Workbench 2/3 style interface (still compatible with
Workbench 1.3), is HotLinks compatible, and supports ARexx. The program is
easily installed using Commodore's Installer (included). The manual is
about 175 pages and contains a wealth of background information concerning
what the various font types are, and how to manipulate them within
TypeSmith.

TypeSmith requires a minimum of Workbench 1.3, 2 floppy drives, 2 MB of
memory (512K of CHIP). Workbench 2.x, a hard drive and a multisynch monitor
are highly recommended.

