@node helm "Helm"

   ____ 
  (_  _)                        Helm Review
   / /                        By @{" John Evers " link johne }
 _/ /  
(____) f you have visited the STARSHIP in the last month, you probably
couldn't escape me talking about an incredible new program called Helm from
Eagle Tree Software. What is Helm? If you took DeluxePaint, CanDo, ImageFX,
and Hyperbook, and rolled them into one program, you would probably get an
idea of what Helm is. Basically, Helm is a software authoring program that
lets you build your own working programs and presentations with a minimum
of effort. I'm talking REAL programs here. In fact, I am typing this review
into a word processor that I made myself! My homemade word processor has
cut, copy, and paste using the clipboard, search and replace, text styles,
and full printing capabilities. It could have even more features if I would
have spent more than 10 minutes making it. Would you like to build your own
paint program? How about an AGA paint program with HAM8 support, image
processing, and animation capabilities? This might take you a bit longer.
Better set aside at least 20 minutes for this one! All this from a guy
who never even wrote an AREXX script! Let me tell you more...

Helm will run on any Amiga with at least 1 meg of memory and at least
Workbench 1.3, although 2.04 or higher is recommended. It will also take
full advantage of an FPU and the AGA chipset. The Helm package comes on 7
disks, but the actual Helm program only takes up half a floppy. The other 6
disks are full of example "Books" and artwork for you to use in your own
creations. The Helm manual is a 336 page work of art. If only all
manuals could be so helpful, comprehensive, and full of examples as this
one. Multiple screen shots and diagrams make this manual the best I have
ever seen for any of my programs! )

The program is very easy to use. Everything you need to make your program
is in Helm, including text editors, and full painting and drawing tools.
You can use Helm's structured drawing tools to make a background, and maybe
add some shapes. Then you add your fields. Fields are rectangles that you
draw onto the screen that can have different functions. You can draw a
Textfield, and enter text into it, or have it import an ASCII file. You can
make an Imagefield, and draw a picture or an animation into it. You can
also draw fields for selectors, timers, buttons, even charts. To every
object, you can add either an action or a script. An action event is a
function you can set up by pointing and clicking. If you really want to get
into it, Helm has it's own scripting language called "Breeze". It really is
a breeze to write a script in Helm. Lets say that I have a button in my
program called "Fishbone", and when I click on it with the left (selection)
button of my mouse, I want the button to turn dark red, and say the name of
the button. Here is the script for that button.

On SelectUp ;when the button is clicked on, and my finger is released
  begin
    set the color of me to dark red
    say the name of me
  end

That's about as hard as it gets, and most of the time, you won't even have
to write a script. Of course, you can get Helm to do more complicated
functions. It has full math functions, serial port control, and can even
control a genlock, a CDTV, or the Picture-in-Picture function of a GVP
IV24 board!

All this good stuff must come at a price, right? Well, the retail price of
Helm is $129, but if you let Eagle Tree Software know that you are a member
of GEnie, you can get the whole package for $79 !

By now I guess you get the impression that I like this product. Your right,
I do. What an incredible feeling it is to think of a program you would like
to use, and then being able to say, "Hey! I can make that myself!" I bought
a number of products over the years that promised me I could program the
Amiga. I couldn't catch the vision of AmigaVision, and with CanDo, I just
couldn't do it. With Helm, I'm really at the helm, and I'm loving every
minute of it.

Helm
