(____)  must confess there's not much software in the MS-DOS world that I
appeals to me. I mean, how many spreadsheets does a person need? but the
one thing I have longed for is the "quick and dirty" software, the kind
that usually has a pronoun in the title like "My Mailing List," "My
Inventory," "My Thermonuclear Bomb" (just kidding on that last one,
folks). I know it is possible to perform the same tasks with a word
processor or general database program, but frankly, that's a hassle. Some
of those small, dedicated programs have finally reached us in Amigadom.

Legendary Design Technologies in Ontario, Canada, produces Address-It!,
an address (and other useful bits of information) database and printer
utility. After entering data, you can sort, and display the information.
The program prints envelopes, labels, address books and telephone rotary
cards. Address-It! also exports to ProWrite, WordPerfect, or ASCII, and
imports from programs which create ASCII delimited files (such as some
databases). Pull down menus, mouse and keyboard shortcuts access
functions.

A @{"record template" system "WDisplay address1"} contains the expected fields: name, address, phones (up
to three numbers, all which Address-It! can dial), and so forth. In
addition, there's a user definable field and room for four lines of
general comments. You type in your data, using the "return" key or mouse
to move between fields. For repetitive items (e.g., states), Address-It!
offers lists of commonly used entries designed to reduce typing. The
program comes built in with lists of salutations, major cities, states,
Canadian provinces and several major countries. A good idea, but I didn't
care much for its implementation. For example, I created a base with
numerous New York, NY addresses. To use the lists, I had to take my right
hand off the keys, click the field name, scroll through the list of
states, and double click on "NY." That's a great deal of work to save
typing two letters. The ratio of moves saved to typing increases with
longer entries, as "New York," I still prefer not having to take my hands
off the keyboard in the midst of typing an entry and grab the mouse. A
way to access the lists by way of the keyboard (e.g., allowing the user
to assign frequently used states to function keys) would be welcome.

A powerful Address-It! feature is a bank of 15 button-like "flags" that
you can define and set. These flag "yes/no" or "on/off" kinds of
variables. Once defined, you click on whichever flags you want to set for
that record. This is more convenient than typing "Y" or "N." If you are
about to enter several addresses which require the same flag(s), you can
set the software to flag automatically each entered record.

Records can be searched by direction (e.g., ascending or descending),
type (i.e., upper or lower case), fields (including ZIP code, helpful for
bulk mailing) and/or specific text. Address-It! will simply find the
records, or find the records and tag them for printing or exporting).
Search parameters are easily entered through mouse clicks.

Address data displays can be as records or in a @{"browse format" system "WDisplay address2"}  In the
latter mode, each record is typed in a single line, allowing an overall
view of the what you've entered. You're able to change the appearance of
the browse format quite a bit; select different fields for display, alter
field size, and even designate the name format.

This list can be printed as a master list. Unfortunately, Address-It!
insists on a Hires screen. I couldn't get it to open in any other size.
This limits the amount of data available on screen without scrolling.

Setting up a printer to work correctly on continuous feed labels can send
you screaming to the funny farm fast. I could have paid for this program
if I had a nickel for each set of labels I've ruined as I've attempted to
print them!  Fortunately, Address-It! handles printing with aplomb. The
program's defaults include three sizes of address book pages, rotary
telephone cards, labels, and envelopes, plus custom settings if none of
the above fits your needs. Those defaults can be altered and saved.
Address-It! automatically provides you with an on-screen preview of your
label or envelope or whatever, so you can proof it before printing.
Additionally for output, the US Postal Service address guidelines (i.e.,
all caps, no punctuation, and city, state and ZIP code on one line) can
be toggled on or off through a configuration menu.

I entered my home address, and tagged it for printing. I loaded a batch
of continuous feed labels into my dot matrix, selected "Print" and let
'er rip. It worked, except the labels were double spaced. The manual
suggested that the page width needed adjustment. I did so, then printed
again. Eureka! The addresses ended up where they were supposed to be!
Single spaced! This sure bets the heck out of mucking around with printer
definitions in a word processing or database program. One small glitch:
the printer remained steadfastly in draft mode, and refused to print in
NLQ. This may be the fault of my preferences driver, though, and not of
Address-It! The program supports HP Lasers, including a landscape option,
but alas, I don't have access to one for testing.

I had some minor trouble with the WordPerfect export. For those of you
not familiar with WordPerfect, its mail merge function requires two
files: a "secondary file" of data fields (e.g., names and addresses) and
a "primary file" (e.g., a form letter). Address-It! exported the tagged
files as a formatted secondary file. However, WordPerfect shrieked that
the file was improper when I attempted to use it. If I pulled the
Address-It! created file into WordPerfect, then saved it back out, the
merge worked like clockwork.

The 39 page, indexed manual guides the user through the program's features
in a concise and quite complete manner. For example, instead of referring
the user to the Amiga manuals, Chapter One discusses the standard AmigaDOS
gadgets used in the program without sounding condescending. Unfortunately,
the manual is as poorly printed as it is well written. The haphazard
printing cheapens the overall package and presents an amateurish
impression, despite the quality of the manual's writing.

Address-It! plugs a very real gap in Amiga software, and Legendary Design
Technologies deserves kudos for this program. It crams a great deal of
functionality and flexibility into a small, well-thought-out package. I
can summarize Address-It! in two words: Buy-It!

Address-It!
