@node imag "ImageMaster 9.23"

    _  _
   / \/ \                   IMAGE MASTER v.9.23
  /      \               by @{" Les And Clive Watts " link watts }
 / /\  /\ \ 
(_/  \/  \_) any graphics enthusiasts will have encountered the numerous
problems of having spent hours producing a masterpiece - only to lose it
before they had time to save it or whilst trying to transfer it into and/or
combine it with, the useful parts of another program for further
treatment.

Image Master is a great leap forward in the relief of this situation - it
accepts almost every type of output format available from the Amiga; it
also CONVERTS them into 24-bit pictures for internal manipulation. Not
only is all the work carried out within this one "Jack of all Trades"
program it is also able to be performed within the more exacting criteria
of this much higher definition mode. You then have the option of
returning it to its original form : 16-colour, HAM, Low-res, Hi-res, with
or without interlace - but now edited in an improved and upgraded
quality, or for onward processing in another 24-Bit program. Be warned
that you can"t change what isn't there - and though importing HAM
pictures into Image Master and manipulating them within this program will
give a much better eventual result, THAT result will not be as good as if
it had been constructed/grabbed into a 24-bit system in the first
instance, before loading into Image Master for manipulation.

I believe the version I tested included the most recent upgrade. However,
parts of the program appeared not to be covered in the manual whereas,
conversely, the manual appeared to describe functions which I could not
find in the program. Such an infinitely variable and complex production
as this program, does need a more simplified guide, if its appeal is to
attract the widest possible selection of the Amiga population, with their
varying levels of competence. Indeed, I suspect that even the most ardent
and experienced graphics enthusiast might encounter difficulties for the
first few hours in trying to avoid the pitfalls of this maze. As it
was, many of my tests had to be done by trial and error and/or with a
little intelligent guesswork.

The programmers seem to hold Digi-View in high esteem. So much so that
special provisions have been provided within this program to accept a
direct input from Digi-View with its hardware installed and that program
running. It is only a matter of opinion but one of my most frustrating
learning curves was with early versions of Digi-View. My results with
it were never satisfactory to me. My best recent frame grabs, from the
lower priced end of the market, were with VideoMaster which,
unfortunately, is aimed at the A500+. As the Image Master recommendation
was for a minimum of 4Mb of RAM [accelerator board only "advised" - so I
left it out], I was obliged to use an A2000. I finally decide to use
Vidi-Amiga 12 for grabbing.

One can see from its requirements that it is a very memory hungry
program. I found 4Mb barely enough. This is because 24-bit programs
absorb roughly four times the amount of memory that a HAM program
might. Logically this, by simple calculation, reduces the "effective"
memory of a 4Mb system, relative to the requirement for a HAM picture, to
that of a 1Mb machine.

Image Master runs on "Buffers" [memories] into which one loads the
various pictures.  The Primary Buffer is where the first picture is
loaded. This is the one immediately displayed on the screen. With only
one picture loaded, the Primary Image, some of the other operations are
"ghosted" and only limited processing of THAT picture is possible. These
operations are controlled by the Process Panel. One should not be
daunted by this, for the Process Panel controls over 70 individual  and
multiple activities - some of which can be combined to produce an infinite
permutation of effects. These include the "standard" adjustments for
colour, gamma, brightness and contrast as well as high/low pass filters and
such special effects as "line art", "smear", "posterise", "water
colour","asterize", "colour key" and "shine" - to name but a few!

The Secondary Buffer is not necessarily the second picture loaded.
It could be a Brush or Clip obtained by cutting out part of the Primary
Image.

An unusual aspect of this program is that there are no preset
"tools" with convenient icons to select them. Everything and anything
seems to be available, with size,colour, shape, etc, at the total
discretion of the user. Even the thickness of the Line Tool is
infinitely adjustable. If you have created a Brush from another
picture, you can use that shape to paint with. There is no magnify
tool as such but as soon as one selects an area of the Primary Image as a
clip or brush it goes into a Secondary Buffer. When swapped with the
existing Primary Image and put on to the screen; no matter how small the
area chosen it is displayed at full screen size. You then have the
ability to manipulate each enlarged pixel. Should you require even more
enlargement you simply make another "brush" from the previous enlarged
brush ad-infinitum. Dependent upon the process being used, each clip
memorises its parent. When you have finished your alterations it can be
returned home to its original size and take its place in the original
picture.

The Process and Paint Panels operate on the Primary Image only but
the Compose Panel operates on the Primary Image using information taken
from the Secondary Image [but held in memory]. All these controlling
panels - the Process Panel the Compose Panel and the Paint Panel in
turn lead into other specific panels which then present about forty more
alternative selection buttons to choose from, many of which then lead
into further panels with many more alternative choices. The permutations
seem endless.

Confused? Perseverance and patience is required. After a few hours
with the program pleasing results begin to appear, during which time you
discover that an accelerator board is ESSENTIAL. Without an accelerator
board it is not unusual for a process to take several minutes. Some of
the more complicated one's take over 25 minutes! Only seconds WITH an
accelerator board.

The Paint Panel is really provided to colour the picture [on
screen] delegated as the Primary Image, with solid colours or tints by
the "normal" methods of area fill/paint. Image Master is not defined as a
paint program but to show its versatility, you could add, subtract,
modify coloured shapes to form respectable pictures. These pictures can
eventually have the special effects treatment from the other parts of
the program applied to them.

It is possible to load Amiga fonts into Image Master and, if text is
made into a brush, it can be "stamped" down in place using "Combine" from
the Compose Panel. You need to load the Colour Text program on the
Amiga to be able to use colour fonts.

I ought to mention to those video-philes interested in the wonders
of Chroma Keying, who have a genlock, this program will enable the
still effect of Chroma Keying under four different headings, each of
which technically allows you to select the Colour 0 to be any one of
the 16 million plus on offer. The four headings are:

Min Merge - this takes the whole of the existing secondary image, reduces
it to the size of the space you have chosen, on the primary, and inserts
it. The Colour 0 is selected by a slider adjustment where you decide to
make the transparent colour brighter than the Primary Image.

Max Merge - This does the same process but the transparent colour is chosen
to be darker than the Primary Image colour of the area in question.

Colour Key Min Merge which offers the same process but this one affects
colours Close to the chosen merge colour.

Colour Key Max Merge does the same again but affects colours far from the
chosen colour.


During the five consecutive [18 hour] days I have worked with this program,
I doubt if I have touched even half of its potential. There are parts of it
which have disappointed me such as "warping", "explosion", "cylindrical
wrapping", and the "oil paint" finish was as disappointing to me as the
"water colour" finish was delightful, but perhaps my subjects were
unsuitable. I had little success with the "Morphing" function. It is simple
enough in its operation, but one can only view it in colour within the
program as a "film strip". However an associate of mine using Image Master
and a 24-bit scanner has produced a very impressive demonstration "looped
morph" in high definition colour - of four different heads.

All in all, ImageMaster is a fantastic program for use on its own or to
"clean up" past favourite "works of art" to extend and improve them for
future use. If you decide you can only afford one program and "value for
money" is of prime importance; because of its overall versatility, Image
Master must be very near to the top of the list.

To those interested in using the Amiga's graphics capabilities
to the full, Image Master really does offer the best of all worlds!

