@node accel "Microbotics' 1230XA A1200 Accelerator"


 ______             The Microbotics 1230XA Accelerator
(__  __)                      by @{" Joe Luk " link joel }
  / /   
 / /  echnology sure has come a long way from the days of the room-sized
(_/  monsters. Measuring less than a handspan in length, the MicroBotics
M1230XA accelerator packs up to 128 megabytes of memory, a 50MHz 68030
processor, a 50MHz 68882 math coprocessor, and a battery-backed clock
into your A1200.

The first thing that will strike you about the M1230XA, besides its tiny size,
is the fact that the board is covered with sockets of all kinds.  A pair of DIP
sockets allow the CPU and FPU to be run at different speeds, though a jumper
allows you to run both off the same clock if desired.  On the reverse side is
a pleasant surprise: a SIMM socket with easy-release metal tabs, not the
extremely frustrating plastic deals used by many boards.  Also socketed are the
clock chip (removable if you already have a clock), and a controller chip.

Because of its elegantly modular design, the M1230XA is available in many
configurations.  Officially, it is available with your choice of a 33 or 50MHz
68030, or 40MHz 680EC030 (MMU-less) CPU, though the configuration software
also supports a 25MHz processor.  The software supports a 68881 or 68882 FPU
at these speeds: 20, 25, 33, 40, 50, or 60MHz (the final case is unlikely
to be available at the current time).  RAM sizes of any binary power (1, 2,
4MB, etc) is supported at speeds from 40ns to 100ns.

Many vendors take advantage of the board's flexibility by "custom-tailoring"
configurations.  For example, my board was shipped from the factory with a
40MHz CPU, no RAM, and no FPU.  I ordered a 50MHz CPU+FPU combination with
4MB of RAM, and the board arrived with those options installed.  Configuration
is stored on an EEPROM (for convenient software configuration), but the
board also has hard-coded factory defaults -- this is how I determined that
my dealer did some custom work on my board.  Though it wasn't factory-pristine,
the board was less expensive because more "shopping" was done for the parts.

Installation of the M1230XA is simple: pop out the trapdoor on the bottom of
the A1200, align the connectors, and push the board in.  Hardware tweaking
is normally unnecessary; there are two jumpers on the board: one which
determines whether or not an FPU is present, and one which enters a special
test mode used to bypass a "confused" EEPROM.  About the only users who will
need to touch the hardware are people with internal clocks already
installed -- disabling the M1230XA clock involves pulling out a small DIP chip.

Once the hardware is installed, you will run into one of the board's
limitations: it does not auto-configure its memory under Kickstart 3.0.
MicroBotics promises that KickStart 3.1 fixes this problem, but in the
meantime you are instructed to run the SetXA configuration utility at bootup
to add the memory.  Because this step takes place fairly late in the
startup, certain libraries will have been loaded into slower CHIP RAM.  Much
of this can be avoided using a PD utility called "ROMTagMem", which adds the
memory much sooner in the boot process.  This utility is available in th
*StarShip* library as file #20534, ROMTAGMEM.LHA, 6016 bytes.

If just putting some FAST RAM into an A1200 makes the machine much faster,
adding a 68030 makes it cruise with the responsiveness of a jet aircraft.
AIBB test results and other notes from my 50MHz version using ROMTagMem
can be found in the *StarShip* library as file #20535.

The M1230XA is also Jim Drew's "official" accelerator for his Emplant
emulator package, due to be released for the A1200 soon.  An MMU is "strongly
recommended" for proper Macintosh emulation, and therefore boards which use
the 68EC030, such as GVP's A1230, are not suitable.

Caveats: in addition to not auto-configuring its memory, the M1230XA has
some small shortcomings.  First, if you have a hard disk and a 25-watt (A600)
power supply, MicroBotics recommends that you get a heftier one.  The board
draws 600 milliamps.  The A500 power supply, which is 10 watts stronger,
has worked for me, but there are other options such as the 200-watt monster
Bigfoot 500 power supply ($129, Micro R&D).

My only other complaint is that at 50MHz, the board runs somewhat hotter
than I'm comfortable with.  I have installed a small fan which sits in the
empty popout space underneath the disk drive, and it has kept the board
at a comfortable temperature.  The heat is not an M1230XA problem per se,
since other people with boards such as CSA's Twelve Gauge have reported
similar discomfort.

The board includes MicroBotics' SetXA configuration software and its RAM
diagnostic software on my rev. 1.0 disk.  It comes with a one-year warranty
and concise but thorough and easy to follow documentation.
Above all, the greatest thing about the M1230XA is that its creators did not
skimp in places which others consider commonplace.  This means high quality
chip and SIMM sockets, a one-year warranty, and room for future expansion
if you buy a less loaded board now.  It also means that seemingly little things
like plastic ears on SIMM sockets won't haunt you.

MicroBotics' suggested USA retail prices as specified in its press release
are:
$399 (40MHz EC030)
$429 (33MHz 68030)
$499 (50MHz 68030)

All prices are without FPU or RAM.

I did some shopping and purchased my board from Memory World, which advertises
a 50MHz board with no RAM or FPU for $349.

