@node conn "The Conner CP30544 540-Meg Hard Drive"

 ______
(__  __)                Fast IDE on the Amiga 4000?
  / /                   by @{" Chris Papademetrious " link chrisp }
 / /  
(_/  here is no doubt about it, the Amiga 4000 is currently king of the
hill when it comes to workstation-level Amigas. Its fast processor, AGA
chipset, and incredible expandability give it the most potential of any of
the Amiga line. One aspect of the Amiga 4000's design has been constantly
criticized since its introduction, and that is the IDE (Intelligent Drive
Controller) hard drive interface built into the machine. Traditionally, the
Amiga has always used the inherently faster SCSI interface for its hard
drives, but the Amiga 1200 and Amiga 4000 were the first machines to break
this long tradition with their integrated IDE controllers. The Amiga 4000
comes with a 3.5" Seagate 3144AX IDE hard drive, and that is where the fun
began.

When I upgraded my trusty Amiga 3000 to a shiny new Amiga 4000, I was
very excited about all the extra horsepower and glitzy graphics. The hard
drive, on the other hand, left me wanting much more. As any proud owner
will attest to, the Amiga 3000's hard drive performance is just about
unparalleled, with startup times on the order of seconds. The Amiga 4000,
on the other hand, had rather unremarkable performance and truly dismal
startup times. The worst problem was that during a startup or a reset, it
seemed to take at least ten seconds to even find the drive! While this
may not seem like much, it was very annoying compared with the
half-second or so it seemed to take the old Amiga 3000. As a programmer
(who crashes a lot) I know that every second during the startup sequence
counts!

As many of you know, I also work at a computer dealer with sells both
Amigas and MS-DOS compatible systems. While building a workstation for a
customer, we attempted to use a Conner CP30544 IDE hard drive as the main
drive. We put together his '486 system with the drive and all the many
various cards required to build a clone. However, when the system was
powered up, the hard drive didn't work! During the entire week, we went
through many different theories and a few different IDE controllers, but
to no avail. Eventually, convinced that the drive was defective, we
ordered a new drive. When the new drive arrived and was installed,
however, the exact same problems resulted. After a call to Conner tech
support, however, we were quite suprised: it turns out that we needed a
special high-speed IDE controller for use with this drive! Hey, I said to
myself, this sounds like an interesting test for the store's Amiga 4000!
I took a screwdriver and the extra drive we now had, and went to check it
out.

Wow! This drive was fast! Formatting a test 20MB partition took a bit
over ten seconds, and when I formatted the entire drive, I began to get
annoyed that it was taking a few minutes until I realized that it was
formatting well over a megabyte per second. Best of all, startups no
longer took forever! As I discovered, the lengthy pause of a stock Amiga
4000 is not due to the IDE controller, but rather the standard Seagate
drive itself. When the drive is replaced with the Conner, startup times
are easily as fast as the fastest I've seen on an Amiga 3000, if not
faster. DiskSpeed 4.1 by Michael Sinz reported very quick performance,
but did make one flaw of the 4000's IDE controller obvious. The IDE
interface uses the CPU to move data around, so during intensive drive
access, the CPU is heavily loaded. In contrast, the DMA SCSI system used
in the Amiga 3000 and A4091 cards leaves the processor free during heavy
drive access.

I am quite happy that I found a hard drive to make my Amiga 4000 reach its
potential. Icons now literally fly onto the screen, and loading all but the
largest programs is almost instantaneous. The stock Seagate 3144AX was
depressing, but by using the Conner CP50540 in its place, I was able to
skip spending the extra money for an A4091 and a SCSI-II drive. Admittedly,
using IDE is still not as fast as using an A4091 SCSI-II controller with a
SCSI-II drive, but for the power-hungry-on-a-budget, this drive and the
Amiga 4000 are a match made in heaven. I couldn't be happier! Well... 

