@node pick "Nick's Picks"


    ______
   / __   )        Nick's Picks: The Downloads of July
  / /  ) /                  by @{" Nick Cook " link nick }
 / /__/ / 
(______/ ear Dr. Download: My boss is an idiot. My job is boring. The
commute is hell. I am so tense when I get home, it's all I can do not to
punt Fluffy, the poodle, into the next state. What should I do?
     (signed) Tense

Dear Tense:
With the stress of everyday living, I suggest you honestly explore your
feelings, share your frustrations with a loved one, take a deep breath,
then blow away anything you can with a withering blast from your laser.

Passively and non-violently, of course.

Zerberk (#19935 ZERBERK12.LHA, 112128 bytes) is Matthias Bock's variation
on the arcade game "Berzerk." You joystick jockey through various levels
(don't touch those pulsating electric walls!) blasting the Centurion Robots
and Elexerion Robots as you go. But beware of the pursuing Otto, the most
loathsome, hideous monster of them all. He looks like a giant, circa 1970s'
happy face! AAAIIEEEE! Now, _that's_ the stuff of nightmares.

Or pick up one of the most disgusting files I've ever seen: ARoach (#20025
AROACH.LHA, 10368 bytes). This, ah, game plants huge, repulsive cockroaches
on your screen. These insects scurry for cover under the nearest open
window. Close or move the window, and the bugs run for cover again. Now,
take your mouse pointer and squish the gross things. Splat! I didn't
promise the results would be neat. You can configure the number of roaches;
if they're squishable or not; speed and the public screen they live on,
among other things. You'll be telling yourself how revolting Stefan
Winterstein's program is...between giggles. Bet your friends don't have
_this_ on Windows! Requires AmigaDOS 2.0 +

If you're jealous because the Windows crowd can play "Minesweeper," Alain
Laferriere's ArmyMiner comes to the rescue (#20022 AMYMINERV1.3.LZH, 68352
bytes)! Armyminer works under 1.3 and 2.0, either on PAL or NTSC. It
requires no external libraries whatsoever. Just point-and-click your way to
oblivion. To be honest, I find Minesweeper games somewhat pointless, but
ArmyMiner is a solid Amiga version.

Tired of the carnage yet? If so, try some mind games. Teachers and parents,
pay particular note to this next group!

Wheel (#20100 AV_WHEEL2.LHA, 22656 bytes) is Jeff Carver's AmigaVision
version of the famous (and copyrighted) game show, W****l o* F*****e. Even
though there's no V**** W****, up to four players can spin the wheel, and
take a crack at solving the problem. Wheel is short on bells and whistles,
but it does include a utility to let you create your own puzzles. And you
thought you'd never say "I'd like to buy a vowel" to your Amiga, did you?
Requires AmigaVision or the AmigaVision Player module, at least one meg of
RAM, hard drive or 2 floppy drives.

Carver's back with Yahtze (#20123 AV_YAHTC.LHA, 21504 bytes) a simple
simulation of the classic board game. Like Wheel, Yahtze is not a game but
rather a complex interactive presentation created with AmigaVision. Just
like the board game, the objective is to get a score in 13 different
categories by rolling five dice.  The highest score at the end of 13 turns
wins. I never understood this game as a kid, and I don't understand it as
an adult. But Carver includes the rules, and the game plays well. Like
Wheel, Yahtze requires AmigaVision or the AmigaVision Player module, at
least one meg of RAM, hard drive or 2 floppy drives.

Concentrate (#20237 CONCENTRATE101.LHA, 121856 bytes) is Jody Gustafsona's
charming computer version of the classic memory game. Two humans can play,
or one human can challenge the custom chip intelligence of her Amiga (set
for one of three levels of competency). You simply click on two cards and
attempt to pick up a pair. If you do, a burst of electronic applause
rewards you (however, the applause at the end of the game sounds
unpleasantly like a rifle barrage). The game sports stereo sound effects,
and includes a MED song you can multitask with the game. I didn't miss the
music; the sound effects were fine. In a creative twist, Gustafsona uses
some familiar WorkBench icons as cards. Also included as a second program
that allows you to create your own card decks. This Shareware program is
worth the $10 fee.

                               * * *

Dere Dr. Downlod:
I kneed help with my arithmatick. I kan't seem to get it. Do youse hav any
sugggestions? By the way, I hod a bachaloers degree frm a phamus
uneversity.
     (signed) Give Me the Ball, Coach

Dear Give:
Try LCD Calculator (#19996 LCDCAL2A.LHA, 47872 bytes). As the name implies,
the program opens a full-screen, multi function, color LCD calculator.
Input your data by way of keyboard or mouse. Be sure to download file
19996--the previous upload crashed on launch (much to author Mike Haas'
embarrassment). This version can save a record of all calculator
transactions in a cumulatively-opened text file, date/time-stamped, and/or
print a hard copy in a format similar to printing calculators, with each
logging destination function independently of each other. LCD Calculator
prefers to live in your Sys:Utilities drawer; any place else may require a
"change directory" command. Shareware, $15.

                                * * *

Dear Dr. Download:
I love Barry Manilow music. My favorite foods are white bread, Tuna Helper
and mashed potatoes. I drive a white, four-dour Chevrolet Impala with an
automatic transmission. My friends say I'm boring. What can I do?
     (signed) Needs Excitement

Zzzzzzz. What? Ah, oh,

Dear Needs:
Well, a couple of files will spice up the ol' computer screen. MagicWB
(#20138 MAGICWB.LHA, 490240 bytes) is a _huge_ download with over 160 files
containing new 8 color WorkBench system icons, over 40 new patterns (bonus:
save those unused patterns! You can import them into DPaint as brushes),
and two new fonts to redesign completely your WorkBench screen. The sample
WorkBench screen grab furnished is absolutely stunning. But before you get
excited, keep a couple of things in mind: (i) to look its best, MagicWB
needs to run in a screen resolution of HiRes Interlace or better, so you'll
need a flicker fixer, a multiscan or non-interlace monitor, or just live
with the flicker; (ii) the icons' files are significantly larger (around
2657 bytes each) than the standard icons (1753 for the largest old icon).
Unfortunately, that stopped my installation right there--I don't have the
hard drive space to spare. You know you've gotten a large download when you
unpack the GEnie file----and find _another_ archive! The MagicWB archive
does provide an icon-driven script to unpack it, but its set to copy the
multitude of files to your System: directory. Given the size of the
archive, I suggest you manually unpack it, and direct the output to a
floppy disk instead. Included are three Install routines, for the new RAM:
icon, the System: icons, and to update the drawer icons. The first two
didn't work for me (I didn't try the last one, though). The text whized
through the console window so fast I couldn't exactly see what went wrong.
I couldn't find anything reading the script through a text editor, either.
The outcome is they didn't work for me. Martin Huttenloher's docs are
concise and understandable, and he includes NickPrefs, an ancillary program
MagicWB requires. Despite not having a rousing success  with MagicWB, I'm
saving this one for the happy day I replace my stock 1084S monitor and move
my BridgeBoard stuff onto its own hard drive. I keep thinking about that
gorgeous WorkBench example--I want mine like it! Shareware - $20.

Another way to punch up the WorkBench is with a new pointer. Pointers 2.0
(#19933 POINTERS2.0.LHA 88064 bytes) contains 120 pointer images. All the
separate pointers, as well as a master IFF graphic showing all of them, are
provided. While the artistic merit of some of these pointers is dubious
(the woman's torso pointer struck me as more gruesome than sexy), you
should find an image to your liking here.

                                 * * *

Dear Dr. Download:
Wimps! The Amiga is for wimps! Music, graphics, games...sissy stuff! A REAL
MAN'S computer has acres of spreadsheets, tax programs spreading as far as
the eye can see, more word processors than a secretarial pool! A REAL MAN
likes to go mano-a-mano with the operating system, asserting his
superiority over electronic nature! REAL MEN want it big and hard! Big hard
drives! Big DOS files! Big .EXE files! Big memory!
     (signed) E. Hemingway

Dear E.:
Loved your story about the big fish. Here's some utilities to add to your
drive.

Billed as the fastest GIF viewer on Amiga, FastGIF II (#20140
FASTGIF2.08.LHA, 48000 bytes) uses a GUI interface, a file-requester,
gadgets, and multiple select to display GIF images. FastGIF II takes
advantage of the AGA chipset and shows the images up to 256 colors. Alas.
other Amiga owners have to settle for 256 color images converted into 32
color greyscale; FastGIFF II doesn't convert into HAM as do some GIF
viewers. That's a bit of a disappointment, but the greyscale conversion is
good, and the program _is_ fast. For $35 shareware fee to French author NN,
you'll receive a registered version of FastGIFF II that allows you to save
a GIF as an IFF.

One thing that "broke" under 2.0 is RAD, the recoverable RAM device.
StatRam (#20051 STATRAM21.LHA, 6400 bytes) is Richard Waspea and Nicola
Salmoria's fast, very recoverable ram drive. It works on any Amiga using
V2.04 or greater. StatRam maintains the remarkable recoverability of the
original VD0, but has now been totally re-written to handle any DOS
filesystem, be named what you like, and give back memory from deleted files
instantly. You have to modify your startup-sequence and perhaps add an
entry to your mountlist, but the directions included for StatRam's
installation are concise and easy to understand.

One of Commodore's more gracious moves recently was releasing the hypertext
AmigaGuide to public domain. A number of text files, docs, and cybermags
(like Viewport!) are turning up in the format. However, AmigaGuide text
files can be huge! Well, necessity is the mother of kludging. Bill
Sorensen's PPguide (#20233 PPGUIDE.LHA, 9472 bytes) shows both PowerPacked
and normal .guide files. It requires the PowerPacker and AmigaGuide
libraries. Install ppguide, e.g., in your "c" directory, then you can
PowerPack your .guides, and view them normally by changing the icon's
default tool to "ppguide." I tried it on July's issue of Viewport, and it
worked just fine.

If you create AmigaGuide files, you'll find Roger Nedel's BadLinks (#20110
BADLINK117.LHA, 22656 bytes) a real timesaver. It automates the tedious
task of debugging. This CLI utility checks a .guide file to see if all the
nodes and links match up. BadLink creates two RAM: text files, one for
nodes, one for invalid links. I used the hapless July Viewport again as a
guinea pig. BadLink quickly checked the .guide, and reported two invalid
links. Opps.

The Guru may be gone from Workbench 2.0+, but his infamous numbers remain!
Alert 1.0 (#20223 ALERT111.LHA, 16000 bytes), by Stefan Zeiger, gives you a
detailed description of the alert number. Just drop the program in your C
directory. CLI and 2.0+ only.

Follow Up
In a review of STARSHIP2.0 last month, I commented that I was having
trouble getting the manual (a Notebook file) to work. STARSHIP's author,
Russ Grasso, dropped me some email to tell me the fix: I needed to execute
an "Assign fonts:" to the fonts included with STARSHIP. That worked! The
manual is gorgeous--47 color pages, some illustrated with astronomy photos
(the manual also a good demo for Notebook!). Russ also wrote that, while
the positions of the stars are accurate, the ship speeds are fiction.

#%@*$#@#*&%#%!!!!!

For me, KastleKumquat (#19976 KASTLEKUMQUAT.LHA, 142464 bytes) is the pits.
Following the instructions in the long library description, I created the
disk. It boots, it loads, it plays music, it hangs. Same problem with
Blaster (#19936 BLASTER.LHA, 290304 bytes), and "Degrader" didn't help.

